Path difference at point P: p = \frac{xd}{D}

**Bright fringes** (p = n\lambda, n = 0, 1, 2, \ldots):
x_n = \frac{n D \lambda}{d}

**Dark fringes** (p = (2n-1)\frac{\lambda}{2}, n = 1, 2, 3, \ldots):
x_n = \frac{(2n-1) D \lambda}{2d}

d = slit separation, D = slit-to-screen distance

Linear width of central maximum (between first minima on both sides):
W = \frac{2D\lambda}{b}

Angular half-width (to first minimum):
\theta_1 = \frac{\lambda}{b}

Full angular width of central maximum:
\Theta = \frac{2\lambda}{b}

b = slit width, D = screen distance

**Key:** Narrower slit \Rightarrow wider central maximum

Minimum angular separation for two sources to be just resolved:

**Circular aperture (diameter D):**
\theta_{min} = \frac{1.22\,\lambda}{D}

**Rectangular slit (width b):**
\theta_{min} = \frac{\lambda}{b}

Linear limit of resolution at distance L:
s = 1.22\,\frac{\lambda L}{D}

Resolving power \propto \frac{D}{\lambda} \quad \text{(larger aperture, shorter } \lambda \text{ is better)}

Intensity of polarized light after passing through an analyzer at angle \theta to its polarization axis:

I = I_0 \cos^2\theta

**Special cases:**
\theta = 0° \implies I = I_0 \quad \text{(maximum, parallel polarizers)}
\theta = 90° \implies I = 0 \quad \text{(crossed polarizers)}

Unpolarized light through one polarizer:
I = \frac{I_0}{2}

Let r = \frac{A_1}{A_2} = \sqrt{\frac{I_1}{I_2}}

\frac{I_{max}}{I_{min}} = \left(\frac{r + 1}{r - 1}\right)^2 = \left(\frac{\sqrt{I_1} + \sqrt{I_2}}{\sqrt{I_1} - \sqrt{I_2}}\right)^2

**Special case** (equal amplitudes, r = 1):
I_{max} = 4I_0,\quad I_{min} = 0 \implies \frac{I_{max}}{I_{min}} \to \infty

Visibility: V = \frac{I_{max} - I_{min}}{I_{max} + I_{min}} = \frac{2r}{r^2 + 1}

**Telescope** (objective diameter D):
\theta_{min} = \frac{1.22\,\lambda}{D}
R.P. = \frac{D}{1.22\,\lambda}

**Microscope** (objective semi-angle \alpha, medium index n):
R.P. = \frac{2n\sin\alpha}{1.22\,\lambda}

Limit of resolution of eye \approx 1' of arc

**General rule:** Larger aperture and shorter wavelength improve resolution.
Electron microscopes use \lambda \ll 1\,\text{nm} for sub-nanometer resolution.

