Unpolarized light of intensity I_0 passes through two polaroids. The axis of the second is at 60° to that of the first. The transmitted intensity is:

(A) \frac{I_0}{8}
(B) \frac{I_0}{4}
(C) \frac{I_0}{2}
(D) \frac{3I_0}{8}

back:
**Answer: (A) \frac{I_0}{8}**

Step 1 — After first polaroid:
I_1 = \frac{I_0}{2} \quad \text{(unpolarized through polarizer)}

Step 2 — After second polaroid (Malus's law, \theta = 60°):
I_2 = I_1 \cos^2 60° = \frac{I_0}{2} \times \left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^2 = \frac{I_0}{2} \times \frac{1}{4} = \frac{I_0}{8}

**Answer: (B) 6 mm**

Width of central maximum = \frac{2D\lambda}{b}
= \frac{2 \times 1.5 \times 600 \times 10^{-9}}{0.3 \times 10^{-3}}
= \frac{1.8 \times 10^{-6}}{3 \times 10^{-4}}
= 6 \times 10^{-3}\text{ m} = 6\text{ mm}

This is the distance between the first minima on either side (= full width of central maximum).

